<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-08-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-08-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="73" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf.184.01502/83:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commission to Negotiate
                                    Peace</gloss> to Lieutenant Colonel <persName type="to">E. J.
                                    Dawley</persName></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-08-01">August 1, 1919</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Misc. 1155. Your telegram of July 28th, quoting letter signed by Gough,
                            Boset, and Dawley acknowledged. Your participation in this letter not
                            understood by American Commission, in view of fact that the sole
                            function of American Baltic Commission is to observe and report on
                            economic, political and military situations. Your undated personal
                            telegram to General Bliss, Supreme War Council,<note n="57" xml:id="d73fn57">Not printed.</note> acknowledged.</p>
                        <closer><hi rend="smallcaps">Am</hi>[<hi rend="smallcaps">erican</hi>] <hi rend="smallcaps">Mission</hi></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>